WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.964 align:middle line:90%


00:00:08.964 --> 00:00:11.952 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:11.952 --> 00:00:24.402 align:middle line:90%


00:00:24.402 --> 00:00:26.360 align:middle line:84%
>>GEORGE NOORY: And
welcome to "Beyond Belief."

00:00:26.360 --> 00:00:28.770 align:middle line:10%
Mitch Horowitz with
us on "Beyond Belief."

00:00:28.770 --> 00:00:30.300 align:middle line:10%
He is a well-known
author, and he's

00:00:30.300 --> 00:00:33.000 align:middle line:10%
going to be talking with
us about some of his works

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:37.080 align:middle line:10%
and the esoteric principles
that have guided America.

00:00:37.080 --> 00:00:38.410 align:middle line:10%
Mitch, welcome to the program.

00:00:38.410 --> 00:00:39.380 align:middle line:10%
>>MITCH HOROWITZ: Thank
you so much, George.

00:00:39.380 --> 00:00:39.715 align:middle line:90%
Great to be here.

00:00:39.715 --> 00:00:41.220 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How many books
do you have out now?

00:00:41.220 --> 00:00:43.553 align:middle line:84%
>>HOROWITZ: Gosh, at this
point, probably about a dozen.

00:00:43.553 --> 00:00:45.503 align:middle line:10%
I started with my
book, "Occult America."

00:00:45.503 --> 00:00:46.670 align:middle line:10%
And I keep turning them out.

00:00:46.670 --> 00:00:46.830 align:middle line:10%
It's great--

00:00:46.830 --> 00:00:48.068 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: And the last one is?

00:00:48.068 --> 00:00:50.610 align:middle line:10%
>>HOROWITZ: The most recent one
is called "The Miracle Club."

00:00:50.610 --> 00:00:53.700 align:middle line:10%
That's a book on the practical
benefits of mind metaphysics.

00:00:53.700 --> 00:00:55.328 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What makes
you so prolific?

00:00:55.328 --> 00:00:56.370 align:middle line:90%
>>HOROWITZ: It's passion.

00:00:56.370 --> 00:00:57.750 align:middle line:90%
It really is passion.

00:00:57.750 --> 00:00:59.820 align:middle line:10%
I am so driven by
my subject matter

00:00:59.820 --> 00:01:02.250 align:middle line:10%
that I just find, as I
discovered at one point

00:01:02.250 --> 00:01:05.160 align:middle line:10%
in my life, I want to write
more than I want to sleep.

00:01:05.160 --> 00:01:07.170 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What got you
so interested in writing

00:01:07.170 --> 00:01:09.772 align:middle line:84%
about America and the
principles behind it?

00:01:09.772 --> 00:01:11.730 align:middle line:84%
>>HOROWITZ: It started
when I was a little kid.

00:01:11.730 --> 00:01:14.460 align:middle line:10%
I was growing up in the borough
of Queens in New York City,

00:01:14.460 --> 00:01:17.280 align:middle line:10%
and I was interested in
astrology, and folklore,

00:01:17.280 --> 00:01:18.540 align:middle line:10%
and superstition.

00:01:18.540 --> 00:01:21.190 align:middle line:10%
And I wondered where all
this material came from

00:01:21.190 --> 00:01:23.910 align:middle line:10%
and why it reached so many
people in American life.

00:01:23.910 --> 00:01:25.440 align:middle line:84%
And I began to
research it, and I

00:01:25.440 --> 00:01:28.200 align:middle line:84%
found that occult and
esoteric principles are really

00:01:28.200 --> 00:01:30.160 align:middle line:84%
in the groundwater
of our country.

00:01:30.160 --> 00:01:31.268 align:middle line:90%
It's part of who we are.

00:01:31.268 --> 00:01:33.060 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Including
Freemasonry for example.

00:01:33.060 --> 00:01:34.620 align:middle line:10%
>>HOROWITZ: Oh,
for real, for real.

00:01:34.620 --> 00:01:36.420 align:middle line:10%
Some of the founders
were Freemasons--

00:01:36.420 --> 00:01:39.480 align:middle line:10%
George Washington, Benjamin
Franklin, Paul Revere,

00:01:39.480 --> 00:01:40.410 align:middle line:10%
John Hancock.

00:01:40.410 --> 00:01:41.650 align:middle line:10%
The list goes on and on.

00:01:41.650 --> 00:01:42.890 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What are
Freemasons anyways?

00:01:42.890 --> 00:01:44.560 align:middle line:84%
I always thought they
were bricklayers.

00:01:44.560 --> 00:01:45.477 align:middle line:90%
>>HOROWITZ: All right.

00:01:45.477 --> 00:01:48.210 align:middle line:10%
It's really-- it's an
esoteric fraternity that

00:01:48.210 --> 00:01:51.540 align:middle line:10%
practices ethical development
through the use of symbols

00:01:51.540 --> 00:01:53.220 align:middle line:10%
and esoteric philosophy.

00:01:53.220 --> 00:01:54.502 align:middle line:10%
They do tend to be secretive.

00:01:54.502 --> 00:01:56.460 align:middle line:10%
At one time, they really
needed to be secretive

00:01:56.460 --> 00:01:58.475 align:middle line:10%
because they believed
in things that

00:01:58.475 --> 00:02:00.975 align:middle line:10%
would have gotten you in a lot
of trouble back in the 1700s.

00:02:00.975 --> 00:02:02.010 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Aha, OK.

00:02:02.010 --> 00:02:04.177 align:middle line:10%
>>HOROWITZ: But they really
commanded the allegiance

00:02:04.177 --> 00:02:07.600 align:middle line:10%
of some very powerful and
deeply substantive people,

00:02:07.600 --> 00:02:09.509 align:middle line:10%
including our own
founding father,

00:02:09.509 --> 00:02:11.039 align:middle line:10%
and they continue to this day.

00:02:11.039 --> 00:02:13.920 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I was going to
say, wasn't this basis

00:02:13.920 --> 00:02:16.682 align:middle line:84%
the beginning of the
Declaration of Independence?

00:02:16.682 --> 00:02:17.640 align:middle line:90%
>>HOROWITZ: Absolutely.

00:02:17.640 --> 00:02:18.540 align:middle line:10%
Absolutely.

00:02:18.540 --> 00:02:22.110 align:middle line:10%
In fact, a large portion of
the signers of the Declaration,

00:02:22.110 --> 00:02:25.560 align:middle line:10%
the framers of the Constitution,
Washington's generals

00:02:25.560 --> 00:02:27.330 align:middle line:10%
were, in fact, Freemasons.

00:02:27.330 --> 00:02:28.860 align:middle line:10%
It was a fraternity
that believed

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:32.230 align:middle line:10%
in the protection of the
individual search for meaning.

00:02:32.230 --> 00:02:35.010 align:middle line:10%
So it fed in to a lot of
our early American ideals.

00:02:35.010 --> 00:02:37.680 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How did they understand
things like the Bill of Rights

00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:38.710 align:middle line:90%
in that era, Mitch?

00:02:38.710 --> 00:02:38.910 align:middle line:90%
>>HOROWITZ: Oh.

00:02:38.910 --> 00:02:39.810 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: How did they do this?

00:02:39.810 --> 00:02:41.477 align:middle line:84%
>>HOROWITZ: It's
absolutely fascinating.

00:02:41.477 --> 00:02:43.410 align:middle line:10%
The Bill of Rights
probably came most

00:02:43.410 --> 00:02:45.900 align:middle line:10%
from the writings of Thomas
Jefferson, who was not himself

00:02:45.900 --> 00:02:50.050 align:middle line:10%
a Freemason, but he believed
in the individual search

00:02:50.050 --> 00:02:50.850 align:middle line:10%
for meaning.

00:02:50.850 --> 00:02:53.700 align:middle line:10%
He believed that above all
else in the New Republic,

00:02:53.700 --> 00:02:56.340 align:middle line:10%
you had to give the
individual freedom

00:02:56.340 --> 00:02:59.360 align:middle line:10%
to arrive at his or her own
conception of a higher power.

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:00.860 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: The
Rosicrucians, were they

00:03:00.860 --> 00:03:02.280 align:middle line:10%
the same as the Freemasons?

00:03:02.280 --> 00:03:03.822 align:middle line:10%
>>HOROWITZ: They
were closely linked.

00:03:03.822 --> 00:03:06.660 align:middle line:84%
The Rosicrucians were an occult
fraternity and brotherhood

00:03:06.660 --> 00:03:09.930 align:middle line:84%
whose writing started to
appear above ground in Germany

00:03:09.930 --> 00:03:11.340 align:middle line:90%
in the early 1600s.

00:03:11.340 --> 00:03:13.800 align:middle line:10%
And they espoused many
of the same ideals that

00:03:13.800 --> 00:03:15.360 align:middle line:10%
later showed up in Freemasonry.

00:03:15.360 --> 00:03:18.110 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Why are these secret
societies so suspicious

00:03:18.110 --> 00:03:19.260 align:middle line:90%
of so many people?

00:03:19.260 --> 00:03:21.510 align:middle line:10%
>>HOROWITZ: Americans have
never really liked secrecy.

00:03:21.510 --> 00:03:23.460 align:middle line:10%
And in fact, there
was a reaction

00:03:23.460 --> 00:03:26.490 align:middle line:10%
against Freemasons
going back to 1826

00:03:26.490 --> 00:03:29.080 align:middle line:10%
during the presidency
of Andrew Jackson,

00:03:29.080 --> 00:03:31.600 align:middle line:10%
who himself was a
Freemason, by the way.

00:03:31.600 --> 00:03:33.240 align:middle line:84%
But a lot of people
back in the day

00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:36.780 align:middle line:84%
were concerned about corruption
in American life, favoritism

00:03:36.780 --> 00:03:38.610 align:middle line:84%
in our legal system,
and they didn't

00:03:38.610 --> 00:03:39.720 align:middle line:90%
like any kind of secrecy.

00:03:39.720 --> 00:03:41.190 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That sounds like today.

00:03:41.190 --> 00:03:43.470 align:middle line:84%
>>HOROWITZ: Yeah, it sounds
a great deal like today.

00:03:43.470 --> 00:03:45.510 align:middle line:10%
And sometimes people
look in the right places.

00:03:45.510 --> 00:03:47.610 align:middle line:10%
Sometimes they look
in the wrong places.

00:03:47.610 --> 00:03:49.950 align:middle line:10%
I think Freemasonry
has actually always

00:03:49.950 --> 00:03:52.020 align:middle line:10%
been a gatekeeper
of good ideals.

00:03:52.020 --> 00:03:54.877 align:middle line:10%
But because they're private or
because they're clandestine,

00:03:54.877 --> 00:03:56.710 align:middle line:10%
people have looked upon
them with suspicion.

00:03:56.710 --> 00:03:58.668 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Mitch, what
would the Founding Fathers

00:03:58.668 --> 00:04:01.750 align:middle line:84%
have said about the Civil War
and about the state of America

00:04:01.750 --> 00:04:02.550 align:middle line:90%
today?

00:04:02.550 --> 00:04:04.050 align:middle line:10%
>>HOROWITZ: They
probably would have

00:04:04.050 --> 00:04:06.840 align:middle line:10%
said that we have to
turn down the discourse.

00:04:06.840 --> 00:04:10.230 align:middle line:10%
We have to start to speak to
one another with less cynicism,

00:04:10.230 --> 00:04:12.540 align:middle line:10%
with less sarcasm,
with less hostility.

00:04:12.540 --> 00:04:15.240 align:middle line:10%
You can't have a democracy if
we're at one another's throats.

00:04:15.240 --> 00:04:17.160 align:middle line:10%
I think they would have been
very concerned about that.

00:04:17.160 --> 00:04:18.720 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, and
that's happening today.

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:19.209 align:middle line:90%
>>HOROWITZ: Without question.

00:04:19.209 --> 00:04:21.089 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: If you were
talking to somebody

00:04:21.089 --> 00:04:23.970 align:middle line:84%
who is on the other end of the
spectrum, who doesn't agree

00:04:23.970 --> 00:04:28.360 align:middle line:84%
with you, or you don't agree
with them, instead of dialogue,

00:04:28.360 --> 00:04:29.340 align:middle line:90%
it's bitterness.

00:04:29.340 --> 00:04:30.460 align:middle line:90%
It's hatred.

00:04:30.460 --> 00:04:31.920 align:middle line:90%
It's fighting.

00:04:31.920 --> 00:04:35.452 align:middle line:84%
We've lost what the Founding
Fathers intended for America.

00:04:35.452 --> 00:04:36.660 align:middle line:90%
>>HOROWITZ: Without question.

00:04:36.660 --> 00:04:39.420 align:middle line:10%
It's the gravest threat
to our democracy.

00:04:39.420 --> 00:04:42.390 align:middle line:10%
Now, personally, I have been
friends for about 10 years

00:04:42.390 --> 00:04:44.640 align:middle line:10%
with Steve Bannon, who was
Trump's chief strategist.

00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:45.440 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:04:45.440 --> 00:04:47.857 align:middle line:10%
>>HOROWITZ: Steve and I have
different political outlooks,

00:04:47.857 --> 00:04:50.820 align:middle line:10%
but we both share an interest
in esoteric spirituality,

00:04:50.820 --> 00:04:51.813 align:middle line:10%
and we are friends.

00:04:51.813 --> 00:04:52.980 align:middle line:90%
We are loyal to one another.

00:04:52.980 --> 00:04:54.597 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You don't
scream at each other--

00:04:54.597 --> 00:04:54.770 align:middle line:90%
>>HOROWITZ: Not at all.

00:04:54.770 --> 00:04:56.250 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: --because you
don't agree with each other.

00:04:56.250 --> 00:04:56.850 align:middle line:90%
>>HOROWITZ: Correct.

00:04:56.850 --> 00:04:57.690 align:middle line:90%
Correct.

00:04:57.690 --> 00:05:00.240 align:middle line:10%
We're friends, and we
build that friendship

00:05:00.240 --> 00:05:03.040 align:middle line:10%
on a common interest in
esoteric spirituality,

00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:06.070 align:middle line:10%
but there's also a closeness
and there's a loyalty.

00:05:06.070 --> 00:05:08.560 align:middle line:10%
And we as Americans need
to start cultivating that

00:05:08.560 --> 00:05:09.360 align:middle line:10%
with our neighbors.

00:05:09.360 --> 00:05:10.890 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Tell me
about Manly P. Hall.

00:05:10.890 --> 00:05:11.280 align:middle line:90%
>>HOROWITZ: Oh.

00:05:11.280 --> 00:05:11.970 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Who was he?

00:05:11.970 --> 00:05:13.428 align:middle line:84%
>>HOROWITZ: One of
my great heroes.

00:05:13.428 --> 00:05:17.250 align:middle line:84%
Manly P. Hall was a scholar
of esotericism and the occult.

00:05:17.250 --> 00:05:19.590 align:middle line:10%
He lived and worked in
the city of Los Angeles

00:05:19.590 --> 00:05:22.140 align:middle line:10%
for most of his
life, died in 1990,

00:05:22.140 --> 00:05:24.180 align:middle line:10%
was friends with
Ronald Reagan, as I

00:05:24.180 --> 00:05:27.030 align:middle line:10%
write about in a new book
called "The Secret History

00:05:27.030 --> 00:05:28.170 align:middle line:10%
of America."

00:05:28.170 --> 00:05:31.620 align:middle line:10%
And Manly wrote a
magisterial encyclopedia

00:05:31.620 --> 00:05:34.920 align:middle line:10%
to a cult thought called "The
Secret Teachings of All Ages."

00:05:34.920 --> 00:05:37.387 align:middle line:84%
It's been the biggest influence
of any book in my life.

00:05:37.387 --> 00:05:38.970 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Wasn't there
a private person

00:05:38.970 --> 00:05:41.310 align:middle line:84%
who signed the Declaration
of Independence

00:05:41.310 --> 00:05:43.527 align:middle line:90%
that Manly P. Hall discovered?

00:05:43.527 --> 00:05:45.360 align:middle line:10%
>>HOROWITZ: Interestingly
enough, Manly Hall

00:05:45.360 --> 00:05:47.550 align:middle line:10%
wrote that at the signing
of the Declaration,

00:05:47.550 --> 00:05:49.710 align:middle line:10%
the spirits of the
delegates were wavering.

00:05:49.710 --> 00:05:51.600 align:middle line:10%
They were worried
that if they signed

00:05:51.600 --> 00:05:53.010 align:middle line:10%
and lost the War
of Independence,

00:05:53.010 --> 00:05:54.140 align:middle line:10%
they would be killed.

00:05:54.140 --> 00:05:57.690 align:middle line:84%
Manly wrote that there was some
secret agent of destiny who

00:05:57.690 --> 00:06:00.570 align:middle line:84%
stood up and gave such a
rousing speech at the signing

00:06:00.570 --> 00:06:03.390 align:middle line:84%
of the Declaration that
the delegates rushed up

00:06:03.390 --> 00:06:05.100 align:middle line:84%
to sign the document,
and the man then

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:06.660 align:middle line:90%
disappeared from the room.

00:06:06.660 --> 00:06:08.940 align:middle line:84%
I think the story is
fanciful, but it did

00:06:08.940 --> 00:06:10.890 align:middle line:90%
capture the ideals of the day.

00:06:10.890 --> 00:06:13.350 align:middle line:10%
And Ronald Reagan was
very influenced by it

00:06:13.350 --> 00:06:16.500 align:middle line:10%
because he retold the story
in speeches throughout the end

00:06:16.500 --> 00:06:17.700 align:middle line:10%
of his career.

00:06:17.700 --> 00:06:19.342 align:middle line:10%
And he used the phraseology--

00:06:19.342 --> 00:06:19.730 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Interesting.

00:06:19.730 --> 00:06:21.855 align:middle line:10%
>>HOROWITZ: --that came
directly from Manly's work.

00:06:21.855 --> 00:06:24.397 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: What was so fascinating
about Manley P. Hall's work?

00:06:24.397 --> 00:06:26.188 align:middle line:10%
>>HOROWITZ: What was
fascinating about him,

00:06:26.188 --> 00:06:28.440 align:middle line:10%
George, is that he produced
"The Secret Teachings

00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:32.640 align:middle line:10%
of All Ages," which is a massive
and magisterial book at the age

00:06:32.640 --> 00:06:34.368 align:middle line:10%
of 27 years old in 1928.

00:06:34.368 --> 00:06:35.910 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How did he
have that wisdom?

00:06:35.910 --> 00:06:37.110 align:middle line:84%
>>HOROWITZ: It's
incredible, isn't it?

00:06:37.110 --> 00:06:37.910 align:middle line:90%
It's a mystery.

00:06:37.910 --> 00:06:39.000 align:middle line:90%
It's a true mystery.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:39.960 align:middle line:10%
He was extraordinary.

00:06:39.960 --> 00:06:43.200 align:middle line:10%
He was not an ordinary man
and that all this material

00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:45.923 align:middle line:10%
could have come out of
him at such a young age,

00:06:45.923 --> 00:06:47.340 align:middle line:10%
it's an enduring
literary mystery.

00:06:47.340 --> 00:06:49.620 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: He kind of reminds
me of a Napoleon Hill type

00:06:49.620 --> 00:06:50.420 align:middle line:90%
character.

00:06:50.420 --> 00:06:53.060 align:middle line:10%
>>HOROWITZ: In a certain
sense, and his output,

00:06:53.060 --> 00:06:55.980 align:middle line:10%
it almost like it
belonged to another age.

00:06:55.980 --> 00:06:59.080 align:middle line:10%
It was almost like he had
this power of prophecy,

00:06:59.080 --> 00:07:00.880 align:middle line:10%
in a certain way, where
something was just

00:07:00.880 --> 00:07:01.680 align:middle line:10%
coming through him.

00:07:01.680 --> 00:07:03.085 align:middle line:90%
He was a remarkable man.

00:07:03.085 --> 00:07:05.460 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You're working on a
new documentary, aren't you?

00:07:05.460 --> 00:07:06.335 align:middle line:90%
>>HOROWITZ: Yes, sir.

00:07:06.335 --> 00:07:09.300 align:middle line:10%
I am working on a new
documentary shot on location

00:07:09.300 --> 00:07:12.900 align:middle line:10%
in Egypt about an occult book
called "The Kybalion," which

00:07:12.900 --> 00:07:15.520 align:middle line:10%
was published here
in America in 1908,

00:07:15.520 --> 00:07:18.040 align:middle line:10%
and it claimed to be a retention
of some ancient Egyptian

00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:18.840 align:middle line:10%
wisdom.

00:07:18.840 --> 00:07:21.150 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Is it tied
into the Kabbal?

00:07:21.150 --> 00:07:23.310 align:middle line:10%
>>HOROWITZ: It's not exactly
tied into the Kabbal,

00:07:23.310 --> 00:07:27.540 align:middle line:10%
but it does retain some ancient
Greek Egyptian wisdom called

00:07:27.540 --> 00:07:30.540 align:middle line:10%
hermetecism, and it really
is a faithful reproduction

00:07:30.540 --> 00:07:31.500 align:middle line:10%
of some of these ideas.

00:07:31.500 --> 00:07:33.260 align:middle line:10%
It's a mysterious
book in its own right.

00:07:33.260 --> 00:07:35.760 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Let's take a look at
a preview of your documentary.

00:07:35.760 --> 00:07:37.126 align:middle line:90%
>>HOROWITZ: All right.

